<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,256,630]" box="[151,1436,256,278]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,256,278]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">1. Main lobe of male cercus elongated and curving weakly at apical half, accessory lobe longer than wide................. 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,256,630]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
- Main lobe of male cercus elongated and curving abruptly at apical two-thirds (
<figureCitation box="[979,1089,285,307]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[167,1425,196,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@27.[162,1425,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Machima species. A–C. M. itatiaia Antunes &amp; Takiya, 2020. A. Male habitus in lateral view. B. Cerci in dorsal and, C. lateral view respectively. F. Ovipositor. D–J. Cerci in dorsal and lateral view: D–F. M. phyllacantha. G–H. M. scalprum. I–J. M. paranensis. (Figs. G–J. after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876251/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 16B,C</figureCitation>
), accessory lobe as long as wide......................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Antunes &amp; Tikiya, 2020" authorityName="Antunes &amp; Tikiya" authorityYear="2020" box="[1096,1436,315,337]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Machima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="itatiaia">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1096,1198,315,336]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">M. itatiaia</emphasis>
Antunes &amp; Tikiya, 2020
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,256,630]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
2. Male cerci elongated, slightly curving upward, inner margin concave with a slight crest-like prolongation from base to tip, distal portion rounded with a small, pointed projection on the dorso-apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[967,1083,373,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[167,1425,196,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@27.[162,1425,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Machima species. A–C. M. itatiaia Antunes &amp; Takiya, 2020. A. Male habitus in lateral view. B. Cerci in dorsal and, C. lateral view respectively. F. Ovipositor. D–J. Cerci in dorsal and lateral view: D–F. M. phyllacantha. G–H. M. scalprum. I–J. M. paranensis. (Figs. G–J. after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876251/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 16D, E</figureCitation>
).................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Burmeister, 1838)" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[1086,1436,402,425]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Phaneroptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phyllacantha">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1086,1248,402,424]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">M. phyllacantha</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Burmeister, H." box="[1261,1429,403,425]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="397 - 756" refId="ref38528" refString="Burmeister, H. (1838) Kaukerfe, Gymnognatha (Erste Halfte: Vulgo Orthoptera). Handbuch der Entomologie, Series 2, 2 (I - VIII), 397 - 756." type="journal article" year="1838">Burmeister, 1838</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,256,630]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="30">- Male cerci elongated but not curving upward, inner margin concave with uniform basal region, without inner prolongations and narrow tip; male cerci armed at the internal base with a spine-like, internally projecting process....................... 2</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,256,630]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
3. Vertex process more evident, short and conical; male cerci shorter and somewhat more robust, main branch moderately sigmoid and distally not strongly falcate, ventro-internal margin with several spaced nodes (
<figureCitation box="[1026,1145,520,542]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[167,1425,196,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@27.[162,1425,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Machima species. A–C. M. itatiaia Antunes &amp; Takiya, 2020. A. Male habitus in lateral view. B. Cerci in dorsal and, C. lateral view respectively. F. Ovipositor. D–J. Cerci in dorsal and lateral view: D–F. M. phyllacantha. G–H. M. scalprum. I–J. M. paranensis. (Figs. G–J. after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876251/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 16G–H</figureCitation>
)... 
<taxonomicName authority="Rehn, 1950" authorityName="Rehn" authorityYear="1950" box="[1194,1436,520,542]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Machima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scalprum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1194,1320,520,542]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">M. scalprum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rehn, J. A. G." box="[1326,1436,520,542]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="271 - 319" refId="ref42693" refString="Rehn, J. A. G. (1950 [1949]) Studies in the Group Dysoniae (Aphidniae of authors) (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae) Part I. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 75 (3 - 4), 271 - 319." type="journal article" year="1950">Rehn, 1950</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,256,630]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<keyLead pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
- Vertex process less evident, rectangular in lateral view; male cerci longer and overall thinner, main branch hardly sigmoid, distal two-fifths sharply bent and falcate, ventro-internal margin without spaced nodes (
<figureCitation box="[1067,1169,579,601]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[167,1425,196,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-22@27.[162,1425,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Machima species. A–C. M. itatiaia Antunes &amp; Takiya, 2020. A. Male habitus in lateral view. B. Cerci in dorsal and, C. lateral view respectively. F. Ovipositor. D–J. Cerci in dorsal and lateral view: D–F. M. phyllacantha. G–H. M. scalprum. I–J. M. paranensis. (Figs. G–J. after Rehn, 1950)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876251/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 16I–J</figureCitation>
)................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Rehn, 1950" authorityName="Rehn" authorityYear="1950" box="[1178,1436,608,630]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Machima" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paranensis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1178,1320,608,629]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">M. paranensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rehn, J. A. G." box="[1326,1436,608,630]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="271 - 319" refId="ref42693" refString="Rehn, J. A. G. (1950 [1949]) Studies in the Group Dysoniae (Aphidniae of authors) (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae) Part I. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 75 (3 - 4), 271 - 319." type="journal article" year="1950">Rehn, 1950</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
